# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1884-louisville-eclipse-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1882 Louisville Eclipse season** was the first season as a Major League club for the franchise.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] The team, which had played for several years as a semi-pro team, joined the new American Association league.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] They finished the season with a 42–38 record, good for third place.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1883-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1883 Louisville Eclipse season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1883-louisville-eclipse-season] The team finished with a 52–45 record, fifth place in the American Association.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-baltimore-monumentals-season] The **1884 Baltimore Monumentals** finished with a 58–47 record in the Union Association, finishing in fourth place.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-baltimore-monumentals-season] This was the only season this version of the team existed, and indeed the only season the Union Association existed.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1884 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 14th season of the franchise.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-boston-reds-season] The **1884 Boston Reds** finished with a 58–51 record in the Union Association, finishing in fifth place (fourth among teams that played a full schedule).
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-boston-reds-season] This was the only season the team existed, and indeed the only season the Union Association existed.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **1884 Brooklyn Atlantics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] It was the first season in the American Association for the team, and they finished the year in ninth place.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The Brooklyn baseball team had played as the **Brooklyn Grays** in the Interstate Association in 1883, where they won the championship.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] In 1884, Charles Byrne moved the team into the American Association, renaming them the Atlantics in tribute to the old National Association Brooklyn Atlantics team.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1884 Louisville Eclipse season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] The team finished with a 68–40 record, third place in the American Association.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] There has been some debate over whom the manager of this club was, with some sources listing the club's starting second baseman, Joe Gerhardt, as manager for at least part of the year, with others crediting team official Mike Walsh with either all or part of the year.
[src:1884-louisville-eclipse-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] Guy Hecker started 75 games for the Eclipse in 1884 and won the American Association Pitching Triple Crown by leading the league in wins, with 52, strikeouts, with 385, and earned run average with 1.80.
